The Complete Story: A Holistic Pilot Design Suite
The application is designed to be a comprehensive pilot design suite that guides a user through every critical stage of experiment planning and setup. It begins with a deep exploration of the existing data, uses those insights to determine the necessary scale of the experiment, and culminates in the creation of statistically pure, experiment-ready groups.
This end-to-end process ensures that every pilot is built on a solid statistical foundation, from initial analysis to final group allocation.
The Final Logic for Your Streamlit Application
The application’s workflow is now correctly structured into four logical phases, ensuring that insights from one phase directly inform the actions of the next.
Phase 1: Data Upload and Baseline Analysis
This is the foundational discovery phase. Before any planning can occur, the user must understand the data they are working with.
	1.	Data Upload: The user uploads their complete historical dataset of potential participants.
	2.	Exploratory Baseline Analysis: The app performs and displays a comprehensive analysis of the uploaded
	•	Descriptive Statistics: Key metrics (mean, median, std. dev, quartiles) for all numerical columns.
	•	Data Visualizations: Interactive histograms, box plots, and bar charts to show the distribution of key variables and identify potential outliers or data quality issues.
	•	KPI Deep Dive: The user selects their primary KPI. The app then provides a focused analysis on this KPI, calculating and prominently displaying its baseline rate (mean) and variance (or standard deviation). These two values are critical for the next phase.
	3.	Identify Stratification Variables: Based on the insights from the analysis, the user identifies other key variables (e.g., demographics, user segments) that influence the KPI and should be controlled for during group creation.
Phase 2: Power Analysis and Experiment Design
With a clear understanding of the baseline data, the user now plans the experiment’s statistical requirements.
	4.	User Inputs for Power Analysis: The user provides the core experimental parameters:
	•	Minimum Detectable Effect (MDE)
	•	Alpha (α) (Significance Level)
	•	Statistical Power (1-β)
	5.	Sample Size & Duration Calculation: Using the baseline KPI metrics calculated in Phase 1 and the user’s inputs, the app calculates:
	•	The minimum required sample size per group.
	•	The estimated experiment duration based on user-provided average daily traffic.
Phase 3: Create a Representative Study Cohort
This phase ensures the pilot’s findings will be generalizable.
	6.	Define Population Proportions: The user specifies the statistical makeup of the target population they want to replicate.
	7.	Proportional Stratified Sampling: The app uses the required sample size from Phase 2 to draw a perfectly sized cohort from the main dataset that statistically mirrors the defined population proportions.
Phase 4: Generate and Verify Final Groups
This is the final execution phase where the balanced groups are created.
	8.	Bin the KPI for Stratification: The app categorizes the primary KPI into bins (e.g., “Converters” vs. “Non-Converters” or quantiles for a continuous KPI) to prepare it for stratification.
	9.	Multi-Variable Stratified Randomization: The app splits the representative cohort into treatment and control groups, stratifying simultaneously on all key variables identified:
	•	The binned KPI (from Step 8).
	•	The population characteristics (from Step 6).
	•	Any other important confounders identified by the user in Phase 1.
	10.	Final Balance Verification: The app generates a conclusive “Balance Check” report. This quality gate uses statistical tests (t-tests, chi-squared tests) to prove that there are no significant pre-existing differences between the final groups, showing high p-values (>0.05) for all comparisons.
Summary of the Final, Corrected Solution
This refined structure places baseline analysis in its proper place at the beginning of the workflow, ensuring the entire experiment design is data-driven.

User Requirement - Solution Implemented in the App
Understand my data before starting - Phase 1: Baseline Analysis: Explore data with stats and visualizations; calculate baseline KPI metrics.
Know how many users I need for my test - Phase 2: Power Analysis: Calculate required sample size using metrics from the baseline analysis and user-inputted MDE, alpha, and power.
Know how long my test should run - Phase 2: Duration Estimation: Calculate required days based on the sample size and average daily traffic.
Make my pilot results generalizable - Phase 3: Representative Sampling: Create a cohort that mirrors the target population using proportional stratified sampling.
Create treatment/control groups - Phase 4: Group Generation: Use randomization to split the representative cohort.
Ensure groups are not statistically different - Phase 4: Multi-Variable Stratification: Stratify on the KPI and other key variables to ensure balance.
Prove that the groups are balanced - Phase 4: Balance Verification: Generate a final report with statistical tests and p-values to confirm group comparability.